But it must be noticed that (1) Horace's purpose would be as well served if he employed to indicate his age a date removed by several years from the actual date of pub- lication: (2) Horace may have wished to bring in in- cidentally a compliment to his friend Lollius (cp. Carm. iv. 9, and Ep. i. 2, 1 note): (3) the consuls of the next two or three years do not appear to have been men of mark, and in some cases, at least, there would have

been metrica] difficulties in introducing their names. Hence there is nothing to preclude us from looking further for indications of the date of publication. Now in Ep. i. 12, 26—28 we have

Cantaber Agrippae, Claudi virtute Neronis

Armenius cecidit: ius imperiumque Prahates

Caesaris accepit genibus minor.

This is a clear reference to the successful issue of the campaign of Agrippa against the Cantabrians in stc. 20, and of the ‘promenade in force' of Tiberius Claudius, the step-son of Augustus, which in the same year resulted in the restoration of Tigranes to the throne of Armenia, and in the cession of the standards won from Crassus by theParthians. The 'same blood- less triumph of Rome is again referred to in Ep. i. 18, 55, 56, where we find mention of the dux
